this
> would only last for less than a minute then all would be fine again. More
> recently I would get this same problem but now I would have to shock(?)
the
> power back on again by turning the headlights on which simultaniously
> results in a quick loss of power to the engine (would almost stall it out)
> but then this (headlight flashing action) gives me my power back again.
>
> Right now when I go to start the car it will usually start but then it
will
> suddenly lose power and stall as if the battery is dead (very very dim
dash
> lights). When this happens I can eventually get it started by just playing
> with the headlight and or ignition switch a few times when it will just
> suddenly come back to life as if there was no problem. If this happens
while
> I'm driving I can get the power back by using my light switch shocking
> method. When I get the this problem while I'm still in the driveway I jump
> out and start wiggling all the battery connections and starter wiring
> connections (which all seem very solid and clean) but this never fixes the
> problem like fidling with the light or ignition switch does which leads me
> to believe their is a wiring problem somewhere else. I have even removed,
> cleaned and replaced the large red wires connections going to the light
> switch and fuse box and still no change in this problem.
>  Over the last year I have replaced the battery, starter (bad solenoid),
the
> positive battery cable connector, and since this problem has been showing
up
> I recently upgraded to a new Bosch (internal regulator) alternator (which
